Got the chance to plant some potatoes with my niece Jai and show her about self-sufficiency 🙌🏾. 

I almost forgot about these potatoes and saw they started sprouting crazy so I decided to plant what I had and multiply them. Potatoes are pretty easy to grow, needing 1-2 inches of water a week and you can get about 5-10 potatoes from one plant so you do the math.

First we filled our cloth garden bags with a mix of my compost from months of fruit/veggie scraps, dry grass, eggshells, coffee grinds, paper towels etc, as well as fresh garden soil to give the potatoes a nice lil nutrient-filled crib to move into. Those worm/larve (aka bug Timon and Pumbaa ate in Lion King) are amazing for the soil because they break down the debris and they’re crucial for turning organic material into compost. 

Then Jai got her workout on as we planted the potatoes sprout side up and she covered them with more garden soil.

To finish I watered with leftover rainwater since it has “nitrate” which is the most easily absorbable form of nitrogen, 1 of the 3 macro-nutrients plants need to glow up and flourish. Use that rainwater people. 

If you want to grow food, do your research and start where you are with what you have. There’s plenty food you can grow indoors if outdoor space is limited. 

Get your garden on and grow your own. 

#gardening #potatoes #blackgardeners #getyourgardenon #selfsufficient #farmerjohnson

These stringbean(s) are ready to harvest 💪🏾

I planted these about 2 months ago in May. I learned about the “Three Sisters” method where you grow corn, string beans, and squash together because they provide different benefits to each other. I didn’t have squash this time, but growing these string beans next to my corn brought me some of the tallest/strongest bean plants I’ve grown. (Jack who?)

These beans came from the seeds of a plant I harvested last year July ‘22 a few videos back. I soaked the seeds for about 12 hours (to soften the outer layer and allow the root an easy escape). Then I planted the seeds into soil mixed with my homemade compost made of kitchen scraps and organic waste. Each plant can produce anywhere from 5-10+ string beans, which means I’ll be having more seeds to replant. 

Green beans, or string beans, are rich in vital nutrients and vitamins K, C, and A. Vitamin K plays an important role in blood clotting and helps build up bones. Vitamin A boosts vision, while vitamin C is a potent antioxidant and both vitamins contribute to the growth and development of all body tissues. 

“Let food be thy medicine, and medicine be thy food.”

#gardening #stringbeans #outdoors #plants #garden #healthiswealth

What are the best ways to know a good watermelon? 🍉

Definitely ready 😮‍💨🍉 

Planted this back in May, and I gotta admit it’s been worth the wait. It wasn’t too high maintenance, just watered it just about every other day and held off on watering as much within the last 10 days before harvesting so it can sweeten up and not be too diluted. The good thing with seeded watermelon is I can replant the seeds for another harvest later. 🙌🏾

“Early evidence suggests that regularly eating watermelon promotes good health and may reduce your risk of chronic diseases such as diabetes, obesity, cardiovascular disease and cancer. This is likely thanks, in part, to its antioxidants, which help protect your body from stress and prevent or slow cell damage.”
-Cleveland Clinic

As always, do your own research.

#growyourown #homegarden #ifyoureadingthisitbeenate #watermelon
